, England, United Kingdom":"Hornchurch, Essex, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","Essex, England":"Essex, England","Dagenham, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Dagenham, Essex, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Mandeville","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Marcel, Andre, Armand, Gabrielle, Camille, Emile, Fernand, Fernande, Gaston, Jean-Paul, Lucien, Michel.","French: habitational name from Mandeville, the name of two places in Normandy, derived from Latin <i>magna villa</i> ‘large estate’, or a variant of <b>Manneville</b>, a habitational name from Manneville, the name of several places in Normandy (see 2 below). Compare   Montville   and   Monville  .","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Manneville (Seine-Maritime, Calvados), Manneville-sur-Risle (Eure), or Magneville (Manche)."],"variants":[{"name":"Mansfield","meanings":["English: habitational name from a place so named in Nottinghamshire. The placename means ‘open land by the river Maun’, from the river name Maun (which may take its name from a hill named with Old English <i>mamme</i> ‘teat’) + Old English <i>feld</i> ‘open country’.","Irish (Waterford): when not an importation of 1, this is an altered form of the Norman name <b>de Manville</b> (see   Mandeville   3).","Americanized form of German and Jewish (Ashkenazic) <b>Mansfeld</b>, a habitational name from a place so called in Saxony."]},{"name":"Manderville","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Mandeville  ."]},{"name":"Manwell","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Mandeville  ."]},{"name":"Manville","meanings":["English (Sussex and Lancashire): variant of   Mandeville  .","Altered form of   Mainville   1, a surname of Swiss French origin (see   Miville  ).","French: variant of <b>Menville</b>, a habitational name from Menville in Haute-Garonne, and also of   Mainville   2."]},{"name":"Mundell","meanings":["Scottish (of Norman origin): variant of   Mandeville  .","Americanized form of German <b>Mündel</b> (or some other similar, like-sounding surname): nickname for someone with a prominent mouth, from Middle High German <i>munt</i>, <i>mündelīn</i> ‘(little) mouth’."]},{"name":"Monville","meanings":["Altered form of French   Mandeville  .","Walloon: habitational name from Monville in Namur province in Wallonia (Belgium), of the same etymology as in 3 below.","In some cases possibly also French: habitational name from Montville in Seine-Maritime or Monville in Calvados, both named with Old French <i>mont</i> ‘mountain, hill’ + <i>ville</i> ‘settlement’."]},{"name":"Mandal","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Chandi, Sanjay, Sankar, Somnath, Aditi, Aditya, Ajit, Amala, Amitabha, Anil, Anirudh, Aparna.","Indian (northern states): from Sanskrit <i>maṇḍala</i>, a word that has several meanings, including ‘sphere’ and ‘halo’.","English (Cumbria; of Norman origin): variant of   Mandeville  ."]},{"name":"Montville","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Emile, Vernice.","Altered form of French   Mandeville  .","French: variant of   Monville  . This surname is very rare in France, found mainly in Creuse."]},{"name":"Manfull","meanings":["English (Midlands): probably a variant of   Mandeville  . Compare   Manville  ."]}]},{"name":"Allice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of   Alison  , occasionally used as a given name in its own right."],"variants":[{"name":"Alison","meanings":["From a very common medieval name, a Norman French diminutive of   Alice .  Despite its early popularity, it became quite rare in England in the 16th century. However, it survived in Scotland, with the result that until its revival in England in the 20th century it had a strongly Scottish flavour."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Allice de Mandeville was born about 1435, in England, United Kingdom. She had at least 4 sons with Thomas Legatt II."},"et":{"about 1435–":"umbes 1435–Surnud","1430–1527":"1430–1527","1461–1549":"1461–1549","1461–1553":"1461–1553","1467–Male":"1467–Surnud","1472–Male":"1472–Surnud","1435–Female":"1435–Surnud","1435":"1435","1467":"1467","1553":"1553","about 1435":"umbes 1435","1430":"1430","1461":"1461","1472":"1472","1549":"1549","1527":"1527","Hornchurch, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Hornchurch, Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Essex, England":"Essex, England","Dagenham, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Dagenham, Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1435–":"noin 1435–Kuollut","1430–1527":"1430–1527","1461–1549":"1461–1549","1461–1553":"1461–1553","1467–Male":"1467–Kuollut","1472–Male":"1472–Kuollut","1435–Female":"1435–Kuollut","1435":"1435","1467":"1467","1553":"1553","about 1435":"noin 1435","1430":"1430","1461":"1461","1472":"1472","1549":"1549","1527":"1527","Hornchurch, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Hornchurch, Essex, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Essex, England":"Essex, England","Dagenham, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Dagenham, Essex, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{